{"timestamp":"2025-10-30T15:37:36.088Z","type":"event_msg","payload":{"type":"agent_message","message":"The frontend image is built from `frontend/Dockerfile:1`, which starts from `node:18`, sets `/app` as the working directory, installs the dependencies declared in `frontend/package.json:12`, copies the rest of the frontend source, and runs `npm run start`. That script launches the Express app defined in `frontend/server.js:5`, which serves the static `public` folder and listens on port 3001 (`frontend/server.js:31`).\n\nWhen you bring the stack up with Compose, the `frontend` service definition in `docker-compose.yml:64` maps container port 3001 to host port 3001 (`ports: - '3001:3001'`). Docker’s bridge network then routes any request that hits `http://localhost:3001` on your machine into the containerized Express server. Because the container runs `npm run start` on boot, the app is already serving traffic—nothing needs to run directly on your host.\n\nInside the container, `BACKEND_URL` is set to `http://backend:3000` (`docker-compose.yml:67`), so the proxy routes in `frontend/server.js:15` and `frontend/server.js:23` talk to the backend service over Docker’s internal network. That backend container exposes port 3000 internally, and Compose ensures it is healthy before the frontend starts (`docker-compose.yml:65`). The net effect is that Docker handles all the wiring: your host only needs Docker running, and the containers provide the frontend site on localhost:3001 with traffic forwarded to the backend service behind the scenes.\n\nIf you want to verify it end to end, the next step is to run `docker compose up --build`, then visit `http://localhost:3001` in a browser."}}
